Certainly! Here's an example of JavaScript code that reads parameters from the URL and stores them in an object:

```javascript
function getURLParameters(url) {
    const queryString = url.split('?')[1];
    if (!queryString) return {};

    const keyValuePairs = queryString.split('&');
    const params = {};

    keyValuePairs.forEach(keyValue => {
        const [key, value] = keyValue.split('=');
        params[key] = decodeURIComponent(value);
    });

    return params;
}

const currentURL = window.location.href;
const parameters = getURLParameters(currentURL);

console.log(parameters);
```

In this code, the `getURLParameters` function takes a URL as an argument, extracts the query string part, splits it into key-value pairs, and stores them in an object. The `window.location.href` gives you the current URL of the page, and then the `getURLParameters` function is used to extract and decode the parameters.

Remember that this code assumes that the parameters are provided in a standard URL query string format like `?key1=value1&key2=value2`. If your URLs have a different structure, you might need to modify the code accordingly.

